snippet.textDisplay:
Couple of questions and observations that I've thought of after watching the trailer a bunch of times.
1. The movie is obviously about time travel but how will time travel be done? From the scene with the ships in the ocean and also the car chase scene at the end of the trailer it looks like whatever device or method they use reverses time but leaves individuals unaffected.
2. How far back in time can they go and is there a limit or some kind of physical or existential risk if they keep doing it? Knowing Nolan I'm sure there is.
3. The trailer mentioned that they were trying to stop something worse than nuclear war from occurring. I wonder what that threat could be? I'm thinking that Nolan created a true villian to fight this time, (maybe the guy holding hands with the lady for that short second on the boat? The music seemed to changed ominously for a second when he showed his face on top of that boat or whatever it was and the sun came in behind him) or some evil organization to stop. That could definitely raise the stakes in the movie. John David Washington and Pattison are definitely some kind of time cops so it will be interesting to see how this part of the story plays out.
3. Who is Nolan consulting about the theoretical and scientific basis for time travel? Movies about time travel can open a can of worms especially when they are trying to take a serious approach about it which I'm certain Nolan is doing. Unlike Interstellar and Kip Thorne there is no real empirical evidence or mathematics that we can rely on for time travel. There is a lot of research out there about relativity and Albert Einstein proved much of it years ago. Time travel is a little more complicated in that it is all theoretical. What model of time travel will Nolan rely on? Will he take the butterfly effect model that seems to be the most popular perspective with movies where one event in the past can influence a multitude of future outcomes or will he take the perspective like Steins gate where time is a river and can only be changed by certain actions or events in the past that are dramatic enough to create another timeline? Or maybe he will do a completely different model or a combination of multiple ones. It really has me thinking and I love the fact that Christopher Nolan not only makes movies that are engaging but thought provoking as well. This is going to be fun.

snippet.textDisplay:
As I understand it...
This organisation whose part the lead actor becomes after passing a test, has the ability to control the flow of time using some machine or some such device.
TENET is a palindrome which also hints the way time is controlled in the movie. The time flows forward naturally. From T to E to N. N is the point of return. If something undesirable happens at N, they hit the button and time reverses from N to E to T. So they are at the starting point again. And then they know what's gonna happen, and they can take different decisions to create different outcomes.
But we don't know!
